TY  - JOUR
AU  - Chen, Qi
AU  - Chen, Xiao
AU  - Schipper, Katherine
AU  - Xu, Yongxin
AU  - Xue, Jian
T1  - The Sensitivity of Corporate Cash Holdings to Corporate Governance
PY  - 2012
Y1  - 2012/12/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhs099
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 25
IS  - 12
SP  - 3610
EP  - 3644
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - The average cash holdings of Chinese-listed firms decreased significantly after the split share structure reform in China, which specified a process that allowed previously nontradable shares held by controlling shareholders to be freely tradable on the exchanges. The reduction in cash holdings is greater for firms with weaker governance and firms facing more financial constraints prior to the reform. The reform also significantly reduced the average corporate savings rate, as measured by cash-to-cash-flow sensitivity. These findings are consistent with the premise that the reform removed a significant market friction, which led to better incentive alignment between controlling shareholders and minority shareholders and relaxed financial constraints. Additional analyses show that the reform affects firms' cash management policies, investment decisions, dividend payout policies, and financing choices differently in private firms than in state-owned enterprises.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhs099
ER  - 



